<div class='story'><a name=471></a>
<div class='whowhen'>DeckTech reports on Thu Sep 23 2004  </div>
<div class='headline'>Wars Spoiler #3 with commentary by DT fave Ken Bradford</div>
<div class='text'>And the next preview...<br />
<br />
<img src="/wars/warspreview4.jpg"><br />
<br />
Ken Bradford our resident expert on all things CCG and thus admin of the Wastelands, has this to say about incapacitated.<br />
<br />
----------------------------------<br />
<br />
It seems as though every card game has a 'character gets -X' to something, <br />
and looks like WARS will be no exception.  From Weight of a Legacy in Lord <br />
of the Rings to Disarmed and Dark Jedi Presence in the old school Star Wars <br />
CCG, the ability to reduce an opponent's stats is seemingly always at your <br />
fingertips.<br />
<br />
The problem with most of these cards are that they're too specialized.  <br />
Weight of a Legacy only worked on Aragorn and then only gave him -1 to <br />
power;  Dark Jedi Presence only worked if you had a Dark Jedi where your <br />
opponent had no Jedi.  It's usually a lot of work for such a small benefit.<br />
<br />
Enter Incapacitated, a card that tries to break that stereotype.  How, you <br />
ask?  Well, it tries for an 'everything and the kitchen sink' approach to <br />
stat reduction, without any of the messy 'spot Aragorn' or 'a character with <br />
a weapon'.  You can play this on any of your opponent's characters and <br />
reduce not just Power, but also Tactics and Defense by 1.   It also has a <br />
nice destiny of 5, making it less of a liability to have floating in your <br />
deck, and when you do draw it you are guaranteed to be able to play it.<br />
<br />
The nicest part of the card is the reduction of Tactics.  In the old days of <br />
spread n' drain for Star Wars CCG, it was a typical strategy to stretch <br />
yourself as thin as possible while still keeping the minimum to draw destiny <br />
at any one site.  With Incapacitated, you can pounce on a squad who just <br />
barely meets that minium, wrecking their ability to defend themselves <br />
properly.<br />
<br />
The power and defense reduction are generally less useful, but might help in <br />
taking down a tank like the Rifleman by lowering his power and defense, <br />
making him more vulnerable to weapons fire as well as pulling down his <br />
massive power just a bit.<br />
<br />
You can play this on your own characters as well, though there seems to be <br />
little reason to do so....unless, of course, you're looking to have EXACTLY <br />
21 power at a site for some reason....hmmm....<br />
<br />
<br />
All in all, this card is far from being a superstar, but it is at least <br />
flexible and can easily yield it's intended benefit, no strings attached.  I <br />
can also see it swinging sealed games, where just having the bodies to draw <br />
destiny can sometimes be an issue.  Will it be a constructed powerhouse?  <br />
It's doubtful, though we haven't seen the rest of the set yet.  What I *can* <br />
say is that it's certainly an improvement on some of it's predecessors, <br />
meaning eventually we'll get a powerful version of a card like this to <br />
really mess with the battlefield and manipulate it to our advantage.<br />
<p><small>edited by DeckTech on Thu Sep 23 2004 </small></div><div class='friend'><a href=/send.php?di=/wars/main/news.php&id=471 target="_blank">send to friend</a> | <a href=/print.php?471 target="_blank">printer friendly</a></div></div><div class='date'> Thu Sep 23 2004  </div><div class='comment'>Remember "brief loss of control"? This is something similar - taking out an opponents destiny draw could be pretty huge... Power -1 is not though.<br />
<br />
This is a tough sell to me as far as playability, tougher even than Dubious David Akers.</div><div class='poster'><font class="bfont"> neal</div><div class='date'> Thu Sep 23 2004  </div><div class='comment'>A good review. I think you hit the nail right on the head with the comment about striking a site with exactly 4 tactics. This card will be huge in those situations.<br />
<br />
One minor comment, which I hope doesn't take away from the fact I still think this is a good article, but I don't think Dark Jedi Presense does what you say it does. Doesn't it add to the power of your characters present? Oh well.. still a good article. (=<br />
<br />
- Enrique</div><div class='poster'><font class="bfont"> Enrique Huerta</div><div class='date'> Thu Sep 23 2004  </div><div class='comment'>DJP doesn't subtract.<br />
<br />
I probably won't play this card; I agree with Neal.</div><div class='poster'><font class="bfont"> John Anderson</div><div class='date'> Thu Sep 23 2004  </div><div class='comment'>I believe "Dark Jedi Pressence" spend one force to double the power of all imperials present with a dark Jedi... <br />
 <br />
I think the card is probably a common, less specific targeting is nice as it lends some flexibility to the card. It does target 3 different aspects of a character card, further flexible... but dosent drasticly effect the character. Surely there will be stronger cards to come.<br />
 I do like the card design and the artwork, both good selling points and hey, its the best darned game mechanic out there.<br />
 Keep me posted on sealed deck and booster drafts. I probably wont jump in full force, but may  grace a few of those "pick - up " events. <img src=/news/smileys/wink.gif> <br />
